        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=11456&TOPIC_ID=2657&FORUM_ID=21&CAT_ID=7&Forum_Title=The+Haven+%2D+Albion+%26+General+Discussion+%2D+DAoC&Topic_Title=Rayhl%3F++Where+ya+be%3F&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="midnightblue" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Pit?</P><P>Hell? </P><P>What?<BR> <BR>Whatever are you talking about Mr. B? I'll tell you about hell, I have recently been given money for an upcoming festivity.....That's right my B-day. I went out to shop for myself and get some goodies and bask in Birthday like joy, you can all imagine my chagrin when I realized that there was absolutely nothing out on the market right now worthy enough to purchase because of this eater of time and “real world” social status. </P><P>I fear I am not the only one that has suffered this unforeseen event. An example?  I bought Tivo to watch TV later because I travel a lot. Now I find myself backing up Tivo data onto videotapes to watch later because of this worse than crack like addiction.</P><P>The setup for the making of a DAOC addict is almost Twilight Zone-esque. The scenario is innocent enough. Your driving by a local electronics establishment minding your own business on your way to some pre-determined location, completely oblivious to the powers secretly at work and the detour ahead. </P><P>Suddenly “The Call” hits you. Out of the corner of your eye you glimpse a shopping center. A slight whisper in your ear comes from nowhere “Stop and browse a second, you have time”. Unable to resist, you do as you have been commanded. The store is like any other store of equal patronage, the aisles labeled clearly to guarantee an expeditious yet costly visit. The routine is quite common with gadget junkies you walk in head straight for your vice of choice be it music, movies, games or hardware gather your booty and leave. </P><P>But, not today? </P><P>Today, you find yourself drawn to one specific thing. You still do not know what that thing is. Yet you move deeper into the maze of commerce. The walk through today is somehow more driven than usual. You pass up everything you would normally peruse, guided still to a place yet unknown. Finally your feet stop in the PC gaming aisle. Your eyes blurry, unable to focus completely yet, you see just one thing. “Pick Me” says the voice. You apprehensively lift the black rather bland package from the shelf and gaze. No longer unsure of why you have stopped here and been brought to this point on this day. The voice in your head rings loud and clear “Buy me, you’ll like me…….You NEED me”. Without hesitation you rush for the checkout counter. You pay and out to your car you go.</P><P>The ride home seems an eternity. What will I find when I install this? I hate games like this. Why should I pay to play a game I have already purchased? All perfectly logical questions to ask at a time like this. Yet you do not stop driving. You don’t even remember where you were going to begin with. All you know is that you have to get to a computer and “Play”.</P><P>And that’s exactly what you do. And to this day you continue to do so. Nights become days and weeks become months. And the only voice you hear now in your head says the same thing, over and over again. “Your so close, you can’t quit now. Just 10 more minutes.” 10 minutes will never just be 10 minutes again. </P><P>Voltan Hawkslayer<BR>“Slayer for the Church of Albion”</P><P><BR><a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
